rder (arrows) demarcating the attached and detachedDescemet's membrane</p></caption><alt-text>Figure 1</alt-text><graphic xlink:href="IndianJOphthalmol-56-241-g001"/></fig><fig id="F2" position="float"><label>Figure 2</label><caption><p>Slit-lamp photograph showing reducing Descemet'smembrane detachment (inset showing magnified view)</p></caption><alt-text>Figure 2</alt-text><graphic xlink:href="IndianJOphthalmol-56-241-g002"/></fig><fig id="F3" position="float"><label>Figure 3</label><caption><p>Comparative postoperative photographs showing reducingcorneal edema with complete reattachment of Descemet's membrane.A. First postoperative week (third postoperative day) and B. Twelfthpostoperative week</p></caption><alt-text>Figure 3</alt-text><graphic xlink:href="IndianJOphthalmol-56-241-g003"/></fig><fig id="F4" position="float"><label>Figure 4</label><caption><p>Schematic diagram showing DM detachment with theaccumulated vancomycin in the intrastromal pocket</p></caption><alt-text>Figure 4</alt-text><graphic xlink:href="IndianJOphthalmol-56-241-g004"/></fig></floats-group></article>